.TH CCM 1 "May 2026" "ccm 1.15.1" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
ccm \- Claude Credentials Manager \(em manage multiple Claude OAuth sessions
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B ccm
.I command
.RI [ arguments ]
.RI [ flags ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B ccm
is a command-line tool for managing multiple Claude Code OAuth credentials.
It allows you to authenticate multiple Claude accounts, import an existing
unmanaged credential, switch between them, view usage quotas and
subscription tiers, and manage their lifecycle (refresh, rename, remove).
.PP
Credentials are stored locally in
.B ~/.ccm/
as individual JSON files named
.IR <uuid> .credentials.json
with permission 0600. Each file holds the OAuth tokens, cached subscription
tier, and timestamps for a single Claude account.
.PP
On Unix and macOS, activating a credential makes
.B ~/.claude/.credentials.json
an absolute symlink pointing directly into the store at
.BR ~/.ccm/ <uuid> .credentials.json ,
so Claude Code always reads whatever
.B ccm
has written. On Windows, where symlinks are unreliable, a wrapper JSON file
carrying a
.B ccmSourceId
marker is copied instead.
.PP
The original
.B ~/.claude/.credentials.json
is backed up to
.B ~/.claude/bk.credentials.json
on first activation and can be restored at any time with
.BR "ccm restore" .
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B login
Authenticate a new Claude account via the OAuth Authorization Code flow with
PKCE. The browser opens to Claude's authorize page; the user pastes the
returned authorization code back into the terminal. A new credential is
created with a UUID identifier, and the account email (fetched from the
profile endpoint) is used as the default friendly name. If the email cannot
be fetched, the UUID is used as the name and a rename hint is printed.
.TP
.B backup
Import the credential currently in
.B ~/.claude/.credentials.json
into the ccm store. If the file is already managed by
.B ccm
(a symlink into
.B ~/.ccm/
on Unix, or a wrapper carrying a
.B ccmSourceId
marker on Windows), the command prints a warning and does nothing. Otherwise
the OAuth tokens are copied into a new
.IR <uuid> .credentials.json ,
decorated with the account email as the friendly name and the subscription
tier fetched from the profile endpoint. The imported credential is
.B not
activated; run
.B ccm use
afterwards to switch to it.
.TP
.BI "use " id-or-name
Activate a credential for Claude Code. On Unix, points
.B ~/.claude/.credentials.json
at the stored credential via symlink; on Windows, copies the credential with
a
.B ccmSourceId
marker. If the token is expired, prompts to refresh before activation.
.TP
.B status
List all credentials in a table with columns: ID (8-char prefix), NAME, TIER
(e.g.
.IR "Claude Max 20x" ),
STATUS (valid/expiring soon/expired), EXPIRES (relative time), and an ACTIVE
marker (*). For each non-expired credential, one line per quota window is
printed underneath showing remaining percentage and reset time (e.g.
.IR "5h: 75% (resets in 1h12m)" ).
Usage data is fetched from all credentials concurrently by default; pass
.B \-\-no\-quota
to skip the fetch entirely (faster, offline-safe).
.RS
.PP
.BR \-o ", " \-\-output " " \fItable\fR|\fIjson\fR
selects the output format. The default is
.BR table .
With
.BR "\-o json" ,
the command emits a stable JSON envelope on stdout of the form
.PP
.RS
.nf
{
  "version": 1,
  "activeId": "<uuid>",
  "credentials": [
    {
      "id": "<uuid>",
      "name": "<friendly name>",
      "tier": "Claude Max 20x",
      "status": "valid",
      "active": true,
      "expiresAt": "2026-04-11T15:30:00Z",
      "createdAt": "2025-01-15T10:30:00Z",
      "lastRefreshedAt": "2026-04-10T12:00:00Z",
      "quota": {
        "fetched": true,
        "windows": [
          { "name": "5h", "used": 25,
            "resetsAt": "2026-04-11T15:30:00Z" }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}
.fi
.RE
.PP
Field contracts:
.B status
is one of
.BR valid ", " expiring_soon ", " expired
(snake_case, stable). A missing tier marshals to
.BR null ,
not an empty string.
.B credentials
is always an array, even when empty, so
.B jq '.credentials[]'
works unconditionally.
.B quota.fetched
is
.B false
when
.B \-\-no\-quota
was passed or when the credential is expired; otherwise it is
.B true
and either
.B windows
(on success) or
.B error
(on failure, e.g.
.IR "HTTP 429: too many requests" )
is populated. Each window reports
.B used
as a percentage (0\(en100, and occasionally higher when upstream reports
over-utilization); consumers that want "remaining" can compute
.BR "100 - used" .
.B resetsAt
is the raw upstream RFC3339 timestamp (the table renderer turns it into a
relative string; JSON consumers get the unmodified value).
.PP
The envelope is emitted as minified JSON (no indentation, one trailing
newline) to keep pipelines compact; pipe through
.B jq
for a human-readable view.
.PP
.B \-\-no\-quota
and
.B \-o
are orthogonal: any combination is valid.
.RE
.TP
.BR "refresh " [ id-or-name ]
Refresh the OAuth token for a credential. If
.B \-a
or
.B \-\-all
is given, refreshes every stored credential concurrently; otherwise an
.I id-or-name
argument is required. The cached subscription tier is re-fetched as part of
the refresh. If the refreshed credential is currently active, the active
credential file is also updated.
.TP
.BR "logout " id-or-name
Remove a credential. If the credential is currently active, prompts for
confirmation unless
.B \-f
or
.B \-\-force
is specified.
.TP
.BI "rename " "id-or-name new-name"
Assign a friendly name to a credential.
.I new-name
must be 1\(en32 characters consisting of alphanumeric characters, hyphens,
or underscores. Names must be unique across all credentials. (Credentials
auto-named from a login email bypass this pattern; rename them to a shorter
handle with this command.)
.TP
.B restore
Undo
.BR "ccm use" :
remove the symlink (or managed copy) and restore the original
.B ~/.claude/.credentials.json
from
.BR ~/.claude/bk.credentials.json .
.TP
.BI "share " id-or-name
Expose a credential over a Cloudflare Quick Tunnel so a remote Claude Code
install can use it without the credential ever leaving this machine. The
command runs a local reverse proxy in CAPTURE mode, spawns
.B "claude -p"
once against the proxy to record the local install's identity headers
(User-Agent, X-Stainless-*, Anthropic-Version, Anthropic-Beta, ...),
transitions the proxy into SERVING mode with a random access token, and
starts a Cloudflare Quick Tunnel pointed at it. A base64-encoded ticket
carrying the tunnel host and the access token is printed; hand it to the
remote side with
.BR "ccm launch \-\-via" .
Requires
.B claude
on PATH for the capture step. If
.B cloudflared
is not already installed, a pinned version is downloaded to
.B ~/.ccm/bin/
on first use. The share session stays alive until Ctrl-C.
.RS
.PP
.BR \-\-bind\-host " " \fIhost\fR
skips the Cloudflare Quick Tunnel entirely.
.I host
is placed verbatim into the ticket as the address the remote should
dial (typical values:
.BR 192.168.1.5 ,
.BR my\-laptop.local ,
.BR host.docker.internal ).
The listener itself is bound to the TCP wildcard address so any host
that can route to this machine can reach it, regardless of the string
passed to
.BR \-\-bind\-host ;
the flag is metadata for the ticket, not an interface selector. The
ticket carries an
.B http://
scheme \(em no TLS \(em so only use this on a trusted LAN or for
container-on-same-host setups. Nothing is downloaded, and no
.B cloudflared
binary is fetched or checked for.
.PP
.BR \-\-bind\-port " " \fIport\fR
pins the proxy listener to a specific TCP port instead of letting the
OS pick. Works with or without
.BR \-\-bind\-host :
in the default tunnel mode it just pins the loopback port the tunnel
forwards to; in bind-host mode it pins the LAN-reachable port the
remote side connects to.
.RE
.TP
.B "launch {" id-or-name " | \-\-via " ticket "} [\-\- " "claude args" ]
Run Claude Code against a specific ccm credential without mutating
.BR ~/.claude/.credentials.json .
Two modes are supported.
.RS
.PP
.BR "ccm launch " id-or-name
\(em local mode. Start a loopback passthrough reverse proxy for the named
credential, refresh it up front if expired or expiring soon, and exec
.B claude
with
.B ANTHROPIC_BASE_URL
pointing at the proxy. The child
.B claude
stays on its normal keychain-OAuth code path; the proxy strips its
keychain
.B Authorization
header and injects the target credential's real OAuth bearer. This lets
multiple
.B claude
sessions run against different ccm-managed credentials simultaneously
without calling
.BR "ccm use" .
Requires
.B ~/.claude/.credentials.json
to exist (its bearer is overwritten on every forwarded request) \(em if
you have never run
.BR "ccm use" ,
do that once first.
.PP
.BR "ccm launch \-\-via " ticket
\(em remote mode. Decode a ticket emitted by
.B "ccm share"
and launch Claude Code against the remote proxy behind it. The tunnel
host and access token are propagated via
.B ANTHROPIC_BASE_URL
and
.BR ANTHROPIC_AUTH_TOKEN .
Does not require a ccm-managed credential on the local machine \(em
the bearer comes from the ticket.
.PP
In both modes, any arguments after
.B \-\-
are passed to
.B claude
verbatim (e.g.
.B "ccm launch <id> -- -p 'hi'"
for a one-shot query) and
.B claude
must be on
.BR PATH .
.RE
.TP
.B "serve [\-\-bind-host " \fIaddr\fR "] [\-\-bind-port " \fIport\fR "]"
Run a local HTTP dashboard for managing
.B "ccm share"
sessions. The server holds multiple concurrent share sessions
in-process, one per credential, each equivalent to a standalone
.B "ccm share"
invocation.
.RS
.PP
Without flags the dashboard binds
.B 127.0.0.1:7878
and requires no authentication \(em loopback is the trust boundary.
Any non-loopback
.B \-\-bind-host
value binds that address literally (e.g.
.BR 0.0.0.0 ,
.BR 192.168.1.5 ,
.BR :: )
and activates an admin token:
.B CCM_SERVE_TOKEN
is used if set (minimum 16 characters), otherwise a 22-character
URL-safe random token is generated and printed once on stderr at
startup. The token is accepted via
.BR "Authorization: Bearer " \fItok\fR ,
a
.B ccm_serve_token
cookie, or a
.BI ?token= tok
query parameter (the startup banner prints a ready-to-click URL
containing the token).
.PP
.B \-\-bind-port
pins the listening port (default
.BR 7878 ).
.PP
The dashboard is a single-page application (vanilla JS, no
framework) that polls a small JSON API:
.BR "GET /api/credentials" " lists every credential in the store"
with a live-session projection;
.BR "GET /api/credentials/<id>" " includes a live quota fetch so the"
View Usage dialog can render it on demand;
.BR "POST /api/credentials/<id>" " starts a session (body"
.BR \fB{"mode":"tunnel"}\fR " or"
.BR \fB{"mode":"lan","bindHost":"<host>","bindPort":<port>}\fR ");"
.BR "DELETE /api/credentials/<id>" " stops one."
The UI shows one row per credential with Name, Tier, Status,
Session state, a View Usage button (opens a dialog), and per-row
actions: Start tunnel, Start LAN, View ticket, or Stop. The share
session orchestration is shared with the CLI \(em starting a
session from the dashboard behaves exactly like running
.B "ccm share"
for that credential.
.PP
The server speaks plain HTTP; put it behind a TLS fronting proxy
on a hostile network. Managed share sessions live in-process only
and do not survive restart. Ctrl-C tears every managed session
down cleanly before exiting.
.PP
Only one
.B "ccm serve"
runs at a time, enforced via
.B ~/.ccm/serve.pid
with stale-PID detection.
.RE
.TP
.BI "completion " shell
Generate a shell completion script for
.IR bash ", " zsh ", " fish ", or " powershell .
Credential
.I id-or-name
arguments are completed against the stored credentials.
.TP
.B version
Print the ccm version, the short git commit the binary was built from, and
the build timestamp (UTC, ISO-8601). The same information is available via
.BR "ccm \-\-version" .
Release binaries built via
.B "make dist"
embed this metadata at link time; a binary produced by a plain
.B "go build"
reports
.IR dev / unknown
placeholders instead, which signals an untagged local build.
.SH CREDENTIAL RESOLUTION
All commands accepting
.I id-or-name
resolve the argument in the following order:
.TP 4
1.
Exact UUID match.
.TP 4
2.
Exact name match.
.TP 4
3.
UUID prefix match (minimum 4 characters). If the prefix is ambiguous
(matches multiple credentials), an error is returned listing all matches.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-a ", " \-\-all
(refresh only) Refresh every stored credential. Runs concurrently; output per
credential is buffered so results are printed in stable order after all
refreshes complete.
.TP
.BR \-f ", " \-\-force
(logout only) Skip confirmation when removing an active credential.
.TP
.B \-\-no\-quota
(status only) Skip the live quota API call. The
.B quota.fetched
field in JSON output is
.B false
and no per-window lines are printed in table mode. Faster and safe to run
offline.
.TP
.BR \-o ", " \-\-output " " \fIformat\fR
(status only) Output format. Must be
.B table
(default) or
.BR json .
Any other value is rejected with exit status 1.
.TP
.BR \-\-bind-host " " \fIaddr\fR
(share and serve) Usage differs by command. For
.BR "ccm share" ,
presence is metadata \(em the value is the host the remote side
should dial, and the listener wildcards regardless of the string.
For
.BR "ccm serve" ,
the value is the literal listener address: empty / 127.0.0.1 / ::1
/ localhost select loopback-only (no auth); any other value binds
that address with mandatory admin token auth.
.TP
.BR \-\-bind-port " " \fIport\fR
(share and serve) TCP port to bind. Defaults: OS-chosen for
.BR "ccm share" ;
.B 7878
for
.BR "ccm serve" .
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Show help for any command.
.TP
.B \-\-version
Print version, commit, and build date. Equivalent to
.BR "ccm version" .
.SH FILES
.TP
.B ~/.ccm/
Credential storage directory. Each credential is stored as
.IR <uuid> .credentials.json
with permission 0600. Contains OAuth tokens, cached subscription tier, and
timestamps.
.TP
.B ~/.claude/.credentials.json
Claude Code credential file. When a credential is active, this is a symlink
(Unix) pointing directly at
.BR ~/.ccm/ <uuid> .credentials.json ,
or a managed copy (Windows) carrying a
.B ccmSourceId
marker.
.TP
.B ~/.claude/bk.credentials.json
Backup of the original credential file, created on the first
.B ccm use
invocation. Never overwritten if it already exists.
.TP
.B ~/.ccm/bin/
Directory for binaries auto-downloaded by
.BR "ccm share" .
Currently holds
.B cloudflared
if it was not already on
.BR PATH .
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B CCM_PROXY
Route all outbound ccm traffic through an HTTP(S) or SOCKS5 proxy. The
value is a URL whose scheme must be one of
.IR http ", " https ", " socks5 ", or " socks5h .
Optional userinfo
.RI ( user:pass@host )
is accepted and forwarded to the proxy via
.BR Proxy-Authorization .
A malformed value fails every command listed below at startup with a
parse error, before any network I/O.
.IP
Affects:
.BR "ccm login" ,
.BR "ccm refresh" ,
.BR "ccm status" ,
.BR "ccm backup" ,
and the reverse-proxy forwarding of
.B "ccm share"
and
.BR "ccm launch" .
.B "ccm use"
is deliberately excluded: activation is a local file operation, and the
opportunistic token refresh it performs on an expired credential runs
against the direct network path regardless of
.BR CCM_PROXY .
If you need
.B use
to go through the proxy, run
.B "ccm refresh"
first in the same shell. Does
.B not
affect
.BR cloudflared 's
own control-plane connection or the one-shot
.B cloudflared
binary download performed on first
.BR "ccm share" .
To proxy
.B cloudflared
itself, set
.B HTTPS_PROXY
in the shell \(em
.B cloudflared
honors it natively.
.IP
Stdlib proxy environment variables
.RB ( HTTP_PROXY ", " HTTPS_PROXY ", " ALL_PROXY ", " NO_PROXY )
are
.B not
consulted; only
.B CCM_PROXY
is respected.
.IP
Example:
.RS
.nf
$ CCM_PROXY=socks5://user:pass@proxy.example:1080 ccm share work
.fi
.RE
.TP
.B CCM_SHARE_DEBUG
When set to
.BR 1 ,
.B ccm share
logs each captured identity header and each forwarded upstream request
(method, URL, and a redacted subset of headers) to standard error.
.TP
.B CCM_LAUNCH_DEBUG
When set to
.BR 1 ,
the local passthrough proxy used by
.B "ccm launch"
.I id-or-name
logs each forwarded upstream request (method, URL, and a redacted subset
of headers) to standard error.
.TP
.B CCM_SERVE_TOKEN
Stable admin token for
.BR "ccm serve" .
Minimum 16 characters. Used verbatim if set on a non-loopback bind;
otherwise a random 22-character URL-safe token is generated and
printed once at startup. Ignored on loopback binds (no auth required
there).
.TP
.B CCM_SHARE_TOKEN
Pin the inbound access token used by
.BR "ccm share" .
When set to a non-empty value matching
.B [A-Za-z0-9_-]+
the value becomes the bearer that consumers must present in
.BR "Authorization: Bearer <token>" ,
keeping the token half of the share ticket stable across restarts so
remote consumers don't have to re-paste tickets. The host half (the
Cloudflare Quick Tunnel URL) still rotates per restart. Whitespace is
trimmed; an empty or whitespace-only value disables pinning and
.BR "ccm share"
mints a fresh random token as usual. Invalid charset rejects startup
with a non-zero exit. Ignored by
.BR "ccm serve" ;
serve sessions are pinned via the web UI instead.
.SH EXAMPLES
Authenticate a new account (credential is named after the account email):
.PP
.RS
.nf
$ ccm login
.fi
.RE
.PP
Import an existing unmanaged
.B ~/.claude/.credentials.json
into the ccm store:
.PP
.RS
.nf
$ ccm backup
.fi
.RE
.PP
List all credentials with quota and tier:
.PP
.RS
.nf
$ ccm status
.fi
.RE
.PP
List credentials without hitting the quota endpoint (offline-safe), or
as JSON for scripting:
.PP
.RS
.nf
$ ccm status --no-quota
$ ccm status -o json | jq '.credentials[] | select(.active)'
.fi
.RE
.PP
Switch to a specific account:
.PP
.RS
.nf
$ ccm use work@example.com
.fi
.RE
.PP
Refresh every stored credential in parallel:
.PP
.RS
.nf
$ ccm refresh --all
.fi
.RE
.PP
Give a credential a shorter name:
.PP
.RS
.nf
$ ccm rename work@example.com work
.fi
.RE
.PP
Restore original Claude credentials:
.PP
.RS
.nf
$ ccm restore
.fi
.RE
.PP
Run Claude Code against a specific credential without switching the
active one (local passthrough proxy):
.PP
.RS
.nf
$ ccm launch work -- -p 'hi'
.fi
.RE
.PP
Share a credential over a Cloudflare Quick Tunnel and use it from another
machine:
.PP
.RS
.nf
# on the host machine
$ ccm share work
Share session for work (4300c4bc) is live.
  tunnel:  https://<random>.trycloudflare.com
Ticket (give this to the remote side):
  <base64 ticket>

# on the remote machine
$ ccm launch --via <base64 ticket> -- -p 'hi'
.fi
.RE
.PP
Share a credential directly over the LAN (no tunnel) so a container on
the same host can reach it without the cloudflared round-trip:
.PP
.RS
.nf
# on the host machine
$ ccm share work --bind-host host.docker.internal --bind-port 8787

# inside the container
$ ccm launch --via <base64 ticket> -- -p 'hi' \\
    --dangerously-skip-permissions
.fi
.RE
.PP
Run the local web dashboard and expose it to the LAN with a stable
token from the environment:
.PP
.RS
.nf
$ CCM_SERVE_TOKEN=<long-random-string> \\
    ccm serve --bind-host 0.0.0.0
ccm serve 1.12.0 is live.
  url:    http://0.0.0.0:7878
  token:  <long-random-string>
  open:   http://0.0.0.0:7878/?token=<long-random-string>
Press Ctrl-C to stop (tears down all managed sessions).
.fi
.RE
.SH PLATFORM NOTES
On Unix and macOS, credential activation uses an absolute symlink from
.B ~/.claude/.credentials.json
directly into
.BR ~/.ccm/ .
Saves to the store are visible to Claude Code without any further action. On
Windows, a wrapper JSON file with a
.B ccmSourceId
marker is copied to
.B ~/.claude/.credentials.json
instead, and
.B ccm
must rewrite this copy (automatically, as part of refresh and rename) when
the underlying credential changes.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
An error occurred.
